<Layout title="Xavier Yin" lang="en" altLangHref="/yuet/" altLangLabel="粵">
	<h1>Xavier Yin</h1>
	<p>
		[ˈzæj.vɪə ˈjɪn]
	</p>
	<p>
		I'm a PhD student from New Zealand in <a href="https://lab-msp.com/">Multimodal Signal Processing (MSP) Lab</a>, part of the
		Language Technologies Institute （LTI) at Carnegie Mellon University (CMU), advised by Prof.<a href="https://carlosbusso.com/">Carlos Busso</a>.
		I currently work on speech articulatory synthesis, particularly text-to-articulatory synthesis.
		Before CMU, I completed my B.S. and M.S. at UC Berkeley, where I worked with Prof.<a href="https://people.eecs.berkeley.edu/~gopala/">Gopala Anumanchipalli</a>.
		My master's thesis focused on the feasibility of text-to-articulatory synthesis as a
		novel approach for speech research. I've also worked on fairness and privacy in large language models
		including linguistic bias, standard language ideology, and data privacy risks.
	</p>
	<p>
		Outside of research, I enjoy traveling, hiking, and rock climbing.
		I also enjoy nature photography, particularly bird photography, and occasionally draw and compose music.
	</p>
	<p>
		You can find my research on the <a href="/research">Research</a> page,
		and occasional writing on miscellaneous topics in philosophy, theology, and other subjects on my <a href="/blog">Blog</a>.
	</p>

	<h2>Mentorship</h2>
	<p>
		I'm not currently accepting mentee applicants directly (undergraduate or master's). If you're
		interested in working with me, please email <a href="mailto:busso@cmu.edu">Prof. Busso</a> directly
		and mention that you'd like to work with me.
	</p>

	<h2>Contact Me</h2>
	<p>
		I'm always happy to hear from other researchers working on related problems, or from anyone
		with questions about my published work. If you'd like to discuss a potential collaboration,
		invite me to speak or review, or simply have a chat, please send an email to:
	</p>
	<p>
		<a href="mailto:nzxyin@cmu.edu">nzxyin (at) cmu (dot) edu</a>
	</p>
	<p>
		&#127475;&#127487; To any Kiwis in the Pittsburgh area who want to meet up, feel free to reach out! I'm always happy to meet fellow New Zealanders.
	</p>
</Layout>
